    <a href="/reading/abstract-algebra/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to algebra</a>

    <h1>Groups</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Tom Judson &middot; GFDL &middot; <a href="http://abstract.ups.edu/">Abstract Algebra: Theory and Applications, Ch. 1</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>group</strong> is a set with one operation that satisfies four axioms: closure, associativity, identity, and inverses. It is the simplest algebraic structure that captures symmetry. Every symmetry you will ever encounter is a group.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. The four axioms -->
    <h3>The four axioms</h3>
    <p>A set G with a binary operation * is a group if: (1) for all a, b in G, a * b is in G (<strong>closure</strong>); (2) for all a, b, c in G, (a * b) * c = a * (b * c) (<strong>associativity</strong>); (3) there exists an element e in G such that e * a = a * e = a (<strong>identity</strong>); (4) for every a in G, there exists a&#x207B;&sup1; such that a * a&#x207B;&sup1; = a&#x207B;&sup1; * a = e (<strong>inverse</strong>).</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; The integers under addition form a group.
; Closure: sum of two integers is an integer.
; Associativity: (a + b) + c = a + (b + c).
; Identity: 0.
; Inverse: -a.

(define (op a b) (+ a b))
(define identity 0)
(define (inverse a) (- a))

; Check associativity
(define a 3) (define b 5) (define c 7)
(display "(a+b)+c = ") (display (op (op a b) c)) (newline)
(display "a+(b+c) = ") (display (op a (op b c))) (newline)

; Check identity
(display "a+0 = ") (display (op a identity)) (newline)

; Check inverse
(display "a+(-a) = ") (display (op a (inverse a)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Integers under addition
op = lambda a, b: a + b
identity = 0
inverse = lambda a: -a

a, b, c = 3, 5, 7
print("(a+b)+c = " + str(op(op(a,b), c)))
print("a+(b+c) = " + str(op(a, op(b,c))))
print("a+0     = " + str(op(a, identity)))
print("a+(-a)  = " + str(op(a, inverse(a))))
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Symmetries -->
    <h3>Symmetries of a triangle</h3>
    <p>The symmetries of an equilateral triangle form a group with six elements: three rotations (0, 120, 240 degrees) and three reflections. This is the <strong>symmetric group S3</strong>, the smallest non-abelian group. Composing two symmetries gives another symmetry.</p>

    <!-- SVG: symmetries of a triangle -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 420 180" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Original triangle -->
        <polygon points="70,20 20,120 120,120" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="70" y="15" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="11">1</text>
        <text x="15" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="11">2</text>
        <text x="125" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="11">3</text>
        <text x="70" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">e (identity)</text>

        <!-- Rotated 120 -->
        <polygon points="210,20 160,120 260,120" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="210" y="15" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="11">3</text>
        <text x="155" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="11">1</text>
        <text x="265" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#f59e0b" font-size="11">2</text>
        <!-- Rotation arrow -->
        <path d="M 195 65 A 20 20 0 0 1 225 65" fill="none" stroke="#f59e0b" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
        <polygon points="225,63 229,67 223,69" fill="#f59e0b" fill-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="210" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">r (120&#xb0;)</text>

        <!-- Reflection -->
        <polygon points="350,20 300,120 400,120" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="350" y="15" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="11">1</text>
        <text x="295" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="11">3</text>
        <text x="405" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="11">2</text>
        <!-- Reflection axis -->
        <line x1="350" y1="10" x2="350" y2="130" stroke="#a78bfa" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,3" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="350" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">s (reflect)</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Permutations as lists: (1 2 3) means 1->1, 2->2, 3->3
; We represent a permutation as a function on indices 1,2,3.

(define (apply-perm p i) (list-ref p (- i 1)))

; S3 elements
(define e  '(1 2 3))  ; identity
(define r1 '(3 1 2))  ; rotate 120
(define r2 '(2 3 1))  ; rotate 240
(define s1 '(1 3 2))  ; reflect (fix 1)
(define s2 '(3 2 1))  ; reflect (fix 2)
(define s3 '(2 1 3))  ; reflect (fix 3)

; Compose two permutations
(define (compose-perm p q)
  (list (apply-perm p (apply-perm q 1))
        (apply-perm p (apply-perm q 2))
        (apply-perm p (apply-perm q 3))))

(display "r1 then r1 = ") (display (compose-perm r1 r1)) (newline)
; rotate 120 twice = rotate 240
(display "r2         = ") (display r2) (newline)

(display "s1 then s1 = ") (display (compose-perm s1 s1)) (newline)
; reflect twice = identity

(display "r1 then s1 = ") (display (compose-perm r1 s1)) (newline)
(display "s1 then r1 = ") (display (compose-perm s1 r1))
; Different! S3 is non-abelian.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# S3 as permutations
def compose(p, q):
    return [p[q[i]-1] for i in range(3)]

e  = [1,2,3]
r1 = [3,1,2]  # rotate 120
r2 = [2,3,1]  # rotate 240
s1 = [1,3,2]  # reflect (fix 1)

print("r1 then r1 = " + str(compose(r1,r1)))  # = r2
print("r2         = " + str(r2))
print("s1 then s1 = " + str(compose(s1,s1)))  # = e
print("r1 then s1 = " + str(compose(r1,s1)))
print("s1 then r1 = " + str(compose(s1,r1)))
# Last two differ: S3 is non-abelian
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. Cayley tables -->
    <h3>Cayley tables</h3>
    <p>A <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cayley_table"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Cayley table</a></strong> records every product in a finite group. Each row and each column is a permutation of the group elements (this is a consequence of the group axioms). Reading the table tells you everything about the group.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Cayley table for Z4 = integers mod 4 under addition
; Elements: 0, 1, 2, 3

(define (mod4+ a b) (modulo (+ a b) 4))

(display "+  | 0  1  2  3") (newline)
(display "---+------------") (newline)
(let loop ((i 0))
  (when (< i 4)
    (display i) (display "  | ")
    (let inner ((j 0))
      (when (< j 4)
        (display (mod4+ i j)) (display "  ")
        (inner (+ j 1))))
    (newline)
    (loop (+ i 1))))
; Every row is a permutation of 0,1,2,3.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Cayley table for Z4
print("+  | 0  1  2  3")
print("---+------------")
for i in range(4):
    row = "  ".join(str((i+j)%4) for j in range(4))
    print(str(i) + "  | " + row)
`} />
    </div>


